<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Command on Margrop Blog</title><link>https://blog.margrop.net/en/tag/command/</link><description>Recent content in Command on Margrop Blog</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-US</language><lastBuildDate>Thu, 25 Feb 2021 15:52:15 +0800</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://blog.margrop.net/en/tag/command/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>How to Run Multiple Python Scripts on Mac with One Command</title><link>https://blog.margrop.net/en/post/one-command-in-mac-execute-mulit-python-scripts/</link><pubDate>Thu, 25 Feb 2021 15:52:15 +0800</pubDate><guid>https://blog.margrop.net/en/post/one-command-in-mac-execute-mulit-python-scripts/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;There are currently 4 Python scripts, and I want to execute all 4 scripts with a single command. How can I do that?
My current approach is rather crude. I used 5 shell scripts to achieve it, but I don&amp;rsquo;t know whether there is a better way.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h1 id="shell-script-runallsh"&gt;shell script &lt;code&gt;runAll.sh&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;"&gt;&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style="color:#75715e"&gt;#!/bin/bash
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt;ls
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt;open -a Terminal.app run17688821.sh
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt;open -a Terminal.app run49763693.sh
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt;open -a Terminal.app run857413.sh
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt;open -a Terminal.app run856853.sh
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>